MapStateToProps = (state) => {
return {
allCats: state.cats,
selectedCatInProps: state.selectedCat // This is the store state
MapDispatchToProps = (dispatch) => {
return {
getAllCats: () => dispatch(GetAllCatsThunk()),
getOneCat: (id) => dispatch(getOneCatThunk(id)) //
- getOneCatThunk() returns an async function to get one cat from the DB
- This async function is dispatched to the reducer BUT gets caught by the thunk middleware before it makes it to the reducer.
- Remember that the reducer should only get an object with a type key on it... so we should get that figured out
- Since the thunk middleware caught a function before it sent it to the reducer, that middleware will invoke the function it caught
- That caught async function is invoked and it now reaches asynchronously to the server to get a single cat based on the id it was passed
e.g. export let getOneCatThunk = (id) => {
return (dispatch) => {
// reach out to api
let {data} = await axios.get(`/api/cat/${id}`); // This will get an object with a key of data that we will destructor to get our data variable
// now lets break about what happens next.....
let objectReturnedFromGotSingleCatActionCreator = GotSingleCat(data)
// This object that is return from GotSingleCat(data) is {type: GOT_SINGLE_CAT, cat: data}
// Now we have a object that is ready for the reducer that holds the cat we got from our api
// Lets send-------> OR DISPATCH that object to the reducer......
dispatch(objectReturnedFromGotSingleCatActionCreator)
// This is the same as this, e.g. dispatch({type: GOT_SINGLE_CAT, cat: data});
The action is a fucntion that outputs an object with a key of type, and could have a payload,
- For something like increment we would not need a payload becuase logically we are just taking the old state of count and adding one to it.
- If you wanted to change state based on user input or api call then you would want that stored in the payload to update state
ThunkMiddleware is in charge of letting objects with key type through to the reducer....
OR
Seeing that a function was dispatched and will need to be stopped from going to the reducer and instead invoked.
When the data is retrieved from the async call it is packaged using an action creator and
then this packaged object (remember looks like this, {type: GOT_SINGLE_CAT, cat: data}) will be sent to the reducer.
reducer delivers the new state
The changes to state are now able to be seen by connected components that put that state on props
